## Hypothesis:

Is it possible to accurately determine the concentration of alcohol based on photographs of cavitation
bubbles using machine learning and computer vision techniques?

## Targets:

The aim of my project work is to train machine learning models and neural networks using computer vision and multimodal data, with which you can quickly find out the concentration of alcohol in various solutions.

## Tasks:

- Training of various machine learning models;
- Creation and training of a neural network;
- Creation of own API;
- Creation of GUI;
- Web service development.

## Formulas for cavitation reserve:

$$
F_g = {m_{gas}g}
$$

$$
F_b = {V(P_{liquid} - P_{bubble})g}
$$

$$
P = {P_{in} - p_{out} = {{2σ} \over R}}
$$

$$
P = {P_σ - P_0}
$$

## Preprocessing:

Two types of data processing were chosen for this project:

- Collection of information about the bubble using computer vision methods;
- Convert the image to a one-dimensional pixel array.

First, let's talk about the first data processing method:

1) Processing, as well as storyboarding of video clips into images from a high-speed camera, was carried out using the OpenCV–Python and NumPy libraries. Preprocessing includes changing the RGB color model to the Gray scale color model, since it is necessary to reduce the number of color layers used, to increase the number of iterations per second, and the methods of the OpenCV–Python library were used to augment the image, namely Gaussian blur, as well as rotate the image to a random degree measure. After storyboarding and image transformation using the OpenCV-Python library, we extract the contour of each cavitation bubble, select the center, and then find the minimum bubble radius to create a circle inside the object of interest. Using this circle, we can find the approximate area of ​​each cavitation bubble, but there is a more accurate way to find the area: using the OpenCV–Python library, we will convert the contour of the cavitation bubble into a graph, thanks to Matplotlib, we will visualize the bubble mode functions, and using the NumPy library, we will calculate the integral to find the area from a function that describes the shape of the bubble. We write all the received data to the dataframe using the Pandas library, as the names of the columns of the generated table, we select:

- Photo name;
- Concentration of alcohol in water-ethanol solution;
- Cavitation bubble area, μm;
- Minimum distance from the center to the edge of the contour;
- Average distance from the center to the edge of the contour;
- Maximum distance from the center to the edge of the contour;
- Standard deviation of contour distances.

Example of collected dataframe:

2) To transfer the image to an array, the Scikit-Image library was used, namely the imread method, which returns an array with a length equal to one of its sides.
Further, in order to speed up the program and optimize training, it was decided to change the image mode to 64x64px using the resize() method. Ultimately, the flatten method was used to convert the multi-dimensional image array to a one-dimensional array.
In order not to translate the image into an array every time in the future, it was decided to save everything in a dataframe. Where 12288 columns are information about the image pixels, and the last column is the concentration index of the water-ethanol solution.

A fragment of the code for converting an image into a one-dimensional array:

```python
data_train = []
labels_train = []

for category_idx, category in tqdm(enumerate(categories)):
    print(category)
    for file in os.listdir(os.path.join(input_path_train, category)):
        img_path = os.path.join(input_path_train, category, file)
        img = imread(img_path)
        img = resize(img, (64, 64))
        data_train.append(img.flatten())
        labels_train.append(category_idx)

data_train = np.asarray(data_train)
labels_train = np.asarray(labels_train)
```

Machine learning models were taken from the Scikit-learn and CatBoost libraries. Before training the model, you need to decide what will be the desired result (y_data), and what will be the data for finding the result (X_data). As the desired result, you need to choose the concentration of alcohol in a water-ethanol solution, and based on the remaining features, patterns will be determined to find the result.
Since in the end this project uses two types of data processing, there will be two types of trained models:
First, let's talk about models trained on data that describe the characteristics of bubbles:
1) To predict the alcohol concentration on these data, classification models were used, namely: KNeighbors, GradientBoosting, RandomForest, CatBoost.

## Neural Network:

The transfer learning method was used to create a neural network. The following architectures were chosen as initial architectures: VGG19 and ResNet50.
VGG19 is a convolutional neural network that has 19 depth layers. These architectures have been trained on more than 1 million images from the ImageNet database and are capable of classifying more than 1000 types of objects in images (computer accessories, animals, plants, chemical elements, vehicles, air transport, bacteria, etc.).
ResNet50 is a convolutional neural network architecture that consists of 50 layers. It is a deep residual network that has been trained on a large dataset of over 1 million images from the ImageNet database. ResNet50 is able to classify more than 1000 different types of objects in images, including computer accessories, animals, plants, chemicals, vehicles, aircraft, bacteria, and others.
Each neural network was trained on 100 epochs, the learning rate was equal to 0.001, and the CrossEntropyLoss function was used as a loss function.
The neural network based on the VGG19 architecture had the Adam optimizer, and for the neural network based on the ResNet50 architecture, the SGD optimizer was chosen.

The prediction accuracy of the neural network based on the VGG19 architecture was 95% on test data.

<img src="img/neural-network/accuracy-on-each-class-vgg19.png" width="450px" height="150px">

<p></p>
The prediction accuracy of the neural network based on the ResNet50 architecture was 90% on test data.

## Own API:

The fastAPI framework was chosen to create the own API, because:
- High performance: FastAPI is based on ASGI (Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface) and uses Python 3.7+ syntax with type annotations. This allows it to achieve high performance and real-time query processing.
- Automatic documentation: FastAPI automatically generates interactive API documentation based on type annotations and comments in the code. This simplifies the process of creating and maintaining API documentation.
- Asynchrony Support: FastAPI supports asynchronous operations and allows you to use the async/await syntax to build efficient and responsive applications.

Link to API Documentation: https://k6zma.ru/docs

The API implements three different methods, namely:
1) «upload_image_for_concentration» - this method takes an image of a cavitation bubble as an input, and a string with the alcohol concentration is returned as an output;
2) «upload_image_for generating_image_normal» - this method takes an image of a cavitation bubble as input, then a contour is selected on the image using the OpenCV library on the image, information about the area and radius of the bubble is collected, then the concentration is determined using a neural network, and all this information is printed on the image, and at the output the user receives the final image;

An example image that we get from method 2:

<img src="img/api-images/generated-bubble.jpeg" width="450px" height="450px">

3) «upload_image_for generating_image_base64» - this is essentially the previous method, it just returns a non-Base64 image to the user.

## Frontend development:

Vue.js framework was chosen for frontend development.
With the help of Vue.JS, the button to upload the image is implemented, and then using the axios library, two post requests are implemented:
1) Post a request to the url "https://k6zma.ru/upload_image_for_concentration" in order to find out the concentration of alcohol from a photo and display the result as a header
2) Post a request to the url "upload_image_for generating_image_base64" in order to display an image with information about the bubble (area, radius), as well as information about the concentration of alcohol in the solution. Since at the output we get a line in the form of base64, it is decoded, and after that the decoded image is displayed on the screen.

Website screenshot:

## GUI:

The Tkinter library was used to implement the GUI, because:
1) Easy of use: TKinter offers a simple and intuitive interface for creating graphical applications. It has simple and clear methods and functions that make the process of developing GUI applications in Python easy even for novice developers.
2) Portability: TKinter is a Python standard library, which means it is available by default on most operating systems. This ensures that your application is portable, as it will run on different platforms without the need to install additional components.
3) Integration with other libraries: TKinter can easily integrate with other Python libraries such as NumPy, Pandas, Matplotlib and more. This allows you to create powerful and interactive applications using the capabilities of these libraries.
